# migrated from tests/cases/numwords.chat (gen346, hermetic + isolated)
[mock hermetic]
!set PARROT0_BASE=
!set PARROT0_SESSION=
!set PARROT0_WORLD_FACTS=0
!set PARROT0_LANG=en
!reset

[test numwords]
# gen112: number words in prose. The word-problem and algebra parsers now read
# number WORDS as well as digits ("three apples", "twelve cookies"), including
# hyphenated compounds ("twenty-one") and multipliers ("two hundred"). The
# mapping is content-word only, so it is language-neutral by construction. Held-
# out words and phrasings; nothing depends on the surrounding sentence template.

# Addition with words.
> Tom has three apples and gets five more. How many apples does he have?
< 8.

# Subtraction with words.
> Mary baked twelve cookies and ate four. How many are left?
< 8.

# Hyphenated tens-unit compound, multiplied.
> There are twenty-one boxes with two balls each. How many balls in total?
< 42.

# Multiplier word: "two hundred".
> A truck carries two hundred crates split among four stores. How many each?
< 50.

# Number words flow into the algebra solver too: "x plus three = seven".
> x plus three = seven
< x = 4.
